''Address of "one"''

*In Mandarin, when spelling a phone number, one on dice or dominoes, one is pronounced {{zh-l|幺}}. This is similar to the English pronunciation of '[[0]]' as '[[o]]' in strings of digits, such as 90210. 

''Tone sandhi''

*See pronunciation section for tone sandhi rules in Modern Standard Chinese.

*In the {{w|Beijing dialect}}, there is a kind of tone sandhi in which {{lang|zh|一}} is pronounced as ''yí'' regardless of the succeeding tone ({{zh-ref|Tao, 2002}}):
{{hide box|Quotation|align=left|
* '''2000''', {{w2|zh|梁左}} and {{lang|zh|梁歡}}, {{w2|zh|pref=《|閒人馬大姐|suf=》}}, episode 7, 18:30
*: {{zh-x|那{nèi} 是 一{yī&#91;yí&#93;} 深夜|It was '''a''' late night|M-BJ}}
}}
:Such ''yí'' is grammatically different from other tone sandhis of {{lang|zh|一}}; it is only used in the structure {{lang|zh|一}} + noun, and only in places where it can be replaced with {{zh-l|一個}}, from which it was reduced.

